'''Acarodomatia''' (singular ''Acarodomatium'') ([[Latin]]: ''[[Acari]]'' - mites, ''domus'' - dwelling), are tussocks of hairs or nonglandular [[trichomes]] located in pits situated in major leaf vein axes of many plant species, occupied and caused by predatory and [[mycophage|mycophagous]] [[mite]]s.<ref>[http://www.everythingbio.com/glos/definition.php?word=acarodomatia Biology definitions]</ref>
