{{Infobox building | image = Front of W. A. Gayle Planetarium.jpg | image_alt = Front of W. A. Gayle Planetarium | caption = Front of W. A. Gayle Planetarium | location = [[Oak Park, Montgomery|Oak Park]] | address = 1010 Forest Ave, [[Montgomery, Alabama]] | coordinates = {{coord|32.368|N|86.287|W}} | opened_date = September 25, 1968 | website = {{URL|https://www.troy.edu/planetarium/}} | map_type = USA Alabama Montgomery Downtown | map_caption = Location within [[Montgomery, Alabama|Montgomery]] | building_type = [[Planetarium]] | seating_capacity = 159 }}
The '''W.A. Gayle Planetarium''' is operated by [[Troy University]] for the city of [[Montgomery, Alabama]]. It provides public presentations and exhibits on [[astronomy]], [[planetary science]], and [[space exploration]].
== Overview == The W.A. Gayle Planetarium is a [[planetarium]] located in Oak Park in the city of [[Montgomery, Alabama]]. Dedicated on September 25, 1968,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wsfa.com|title=Editorial: The Planetarium Dedication|last=|first=|date=September 26, 1968|work=WSFA-TV|access-date=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref> the planetarium is named after [[W. A. Gayle|William Armistead Gayle]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.montgomerybotanicalgardens.com/about/|title=ABOUT {{!}} Montgomery Botanical Gardens|work=Montgomery Botanical Gardens|access-date=2017-10-11|language=en-US}}</ref> mayor of Montgomery from 1952 to 1959. It is currently operated by Troy University for the City of Montgomery.
Daily public shows typically offer visitors a full-dome movie about a current topic in astronomy and planetary science. Interactive presentations provide a tour of the night sky over Montgomery, pointing out what [[Planet|planets]], [[Star|stars]], and [[Constellation|constellations]] can be seen overhead. The 159-seat theater uses a Super MediaGlobe II digital projection system (installed in 2014<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wsfa.com/story/24513758/wa-gayle-planetarium-to-close-for-major-upgrade|title=W.A. Gayle planetarium in Montgomery to reopen March 9|last=Staff|first=WSFA 12 News|access-date=2017-10-11|language=en}}</ref>) to simulate the night sky. Other exhibits include a scale model of the [[Hubble Space Telescope]], images of celestial objects, and a black lit hallway depicting the history of astronomy<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.midtownmontgomeryliving.com/?p=36357|title=Stars Shine at the W.A. Gayle Planetarium|date=2012-08-15|work=Midtown Montgomery Living|access-date=2017-10-11|language=en-US}}</ref>. The planetarium is currently closed on Saturdays.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.troy.edu/planetarium/|title=troy.edu - W.A. Gayle Planetarium|website=www.troy.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-10-09}}</ref>
